    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="18"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d18">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/505</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 656</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-26">January 26,
                            1934</date>.<lb/>[Received February 10.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: On passing through Tokyo today en route from his
                    post at Seoul to Vancouver, Consul General Davis told me that in his farewell
                    interview with Lieutenant General Kawashima, in command of the troops in Chosen,
                    the General spoke with enthusiasm of the great progress and development in the
                    arts of civilization which had taken place in Japan and added his hope that the
                    oppressed and suffering people of Manchuria, China and Siberia would soon be
                    enabled to share these Heaven-sent gifts. The foregoing is not a precise
                    quotation but conveys the sense of the General’s remarks as repeated to me by
                    Mr. Davis. They represent, perhaps, the thoughts of a certain type of Japanese
                    military mind.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph C. Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
